gether leading environmental thinkers from the natural sciences, geography, political science, religion, and philosophy to explore the complex facets of boundary formation and negotiation at the heart of our environmental problems. The contributors provide a fresh look at how our lives depend on the lines drawn and ask how those lines must be reinscribed, blurred, or even erased to prepare for a sustainable future.Resolving environmental problems calls for the negotiation of multiple, intersecting boundaries—natural, social, political, geographical, and ethical. From the differentiation of species to the formation of communities and moral values, environmental theorists are constantly confronted with a palimpsest of thresholds and mappings: Can nature and culture be divided? Are natural divisions discovered or created? How do political borders and moral economies shape community-building and social transformation?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBoundaries (Philosophy). 0aEnvironmental ethics. 0aEnvironmental protection. 0aHuman ecologyxPhilosophy. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Ecology. 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh1 aArnold, T. Clay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Charles S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Charles S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCallicott, J. Baird, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDempster, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelley, Strachan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlover, Jerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsch, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo